<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="278" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[811,1455,1874,2027]" pageId="21" pageNumber="278">
REMARK 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1842" box="[813,906,1906,1931]" class="Asteroidea" family="Echinasteridae" genus="Echinaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spinulosida" pageId="21" pageNumber="278" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis box="[813,906,1906,1931]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="278">E. crassus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits Indian Seas according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Dujardin &amp; Hupe" firstAuthor="Dujardin" pageId="21" pageNumber="278" refId="ref43636" refString="DUJARDIN F. &amp; HUPE H. 1862. - Histoire naturelle des zoophytes echinodermes. Librairie encyclopedique De Roret, Paris, 625 p. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 10122" type="book" year="1862">Dujardin &amp; Hupé (1862)</bibRefCitation>
. The species shares all the characteristics of the common Indian Ocean species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1869" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[1033,1241,1969,1995]" class="Asteroidea" family="Echinasteridae" genus="Echinaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spinulosida" pageId="21" pageNumber="278" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="purpureus">
<emphasis box="[1033,1241,1969,1995]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="278">Echinaster purpureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, having a reticulated skeleton and abactinal plates arranged in longitudinal series.
</paragraph>
